# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: synthetic-monitoring-deep
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] In the fields of information technology and systems management, **application performance management** (**APM**) is the monitoring and management of the performance and availability of software applications.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] APM strives to detect and diagnose complex application performance problems to maintain an expected level of service.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] The term monitoring was replaced by many tool vendors by the term Observability.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] Often, monitoring is seen as the technical process of data collection, whereas observability is seen as the capability to understand a systems behavior.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] Two sets of performance metrics are closely monitored.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] The first set of performance metrics defines the performance experienced by end-users of the application.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] One example of performance is average response times under peak load.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] The second set of performance metrics measures the computational resources used by the application for the load, indicating whether there is adequate capacity to support the load, as well as possible locations of a performance bottleneck.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] Measurement of these quantities establishes an empirical performance baseline for the application.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] The baseline can then be used to detect changes in performance.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] Changes in performance can be correlated with external events and subsequently used to predict future changes in application performance.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] The use of APM is common for Web applications, which lends itself best to the more detailed monitoring techniques.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] In addition to measuring response time for a user, response times for components of a Web application can also be monitored to help pinpoint causes of delay.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] There also exist HTTP appliances that can decode transaction-specific response times at the Web server layer of the application.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] Measuring application performance causes overhead, that might also influence the user experience.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] The overhead can be reduced by several technical measures, including reducing the amount of monitored events and aggregation of data before serialization.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] Since the first half of 2013, APM has entered into a period of intense competition in technology and strategy with a multiplicity of vendors and viewpoints.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] This has caused an upheaval in the marketplace with vendors from unrelated backgrounds (including network monitoring, systems management, application instrumentation, and web performance monitoring) adopting messaging around APM.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] As a result, the term APM has become diluted and has evolved into a concept for managing application performance across many diverse computing platforms, rather than a single market.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] With so many vendors to choose from, selecting one can be a challenge.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] It is important to evaluate each carefully to ensure its capabilities meet your needs.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] Two challenges for implementing APM are (1) it can be difficult to instrument an application to monitor application performance, especially among components of an application, and (2) applications can be virtualized, which increases the variability of the measurements.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] To alleviate the first problem application service management (ASM) provides an application-centric approach, where business service performance visibility is a key objective.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] The second aspect present in distributed, virtual and cloud-based applications poses a unique challenge for application performance monitoring because most of the key system components are no longer hosted on a single machine.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] Each function is now likely to have been designed as an Internet service that runs on multiple virtualized systems.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] The applications themselves are very likely to be moving from one system to another to meet service-level objectives and deal with momentary outages.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] Applications themselves are becoming increasingly difficult to manage as they move toward highly distributed, multi-tier, multi-element constructs that in many cases rely on application development frameworks such as .NET or Java.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] The APM Conceptual Framework was designed to help prioritize an approach on what to focus on first for quick implementation and overall understanding of the five-dimensional APM model.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] The framework slide outlines three areas of focus for each dimension and describes their potential benefits.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] Measuring the transit of traffic from user request to data and back again is part of capturing the end-user experience (EUE).
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] The outcome of this measuring is referred to as Real-time Application monitoring (aka Top-Down monitoring), which has two components, passive and active.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] Passive monitoring is usually an agentless appliance implemented using network port mirroring.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] A key feature to consider is the ability to support multi-component analytics (e.g., database, client/browser).
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] Active monitoring, on the other hand, consists of synthetic probes and web robots predefined to report system availability and business transactions.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] Active monitoring is a good complement to passive monitoring; together, these two components help provide visibility into application health during off-peak hours when transaction volume is low.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] When preparing to implement a runtime application architecture, it is necessary to ensure that up/down monitoring is in place for all nodes and servers within the environment (aka, bottom-up monitoring).
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] This helps lay the foundation for event correlation and provides the basis for a general understanding of how network topologies interact with application architectures.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] Focus on user-defined transactions or the URL page definitions that have some meaning to the business community.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] For example, if there are 200 to 300 unique page definitions for a given application, group them into 8–12 high-level categories.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] This allows for meaningful SLA reports, and provides trending information on application performance from a business perspective: start with broad categories and refine them over time.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] For a deeper understanding, see Business transaction management.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] Deep dive component monitoring (DDCM) requires an agent installation and is generally targeted at middleware, focusing on web, application, and messaging servers.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] It should provide a real-time view of the J2EE and .NET stacks, tying them back to the user-defined business transactions.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] A robust monitor shows a clear path from code execution (e.g., spring and struts) to the URL rendered, and finally to the user request.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/application-performance-management] Since DDCM is closely related to the second dimension in the APM model, most products in this field also provide application discovery dependency mapping (ADDM) as part of their offering.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/ping-networking-utility] Ping measures the round-trip time for messages sent from the originating host to a destination computer that are echoed back to the source.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/ping-networking-utility] The name comes from active sonar terminology that sends a pulse of sound and listens for the echo to detect objects under water.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/ping-networking-utility] Ping operates by means of Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) packets.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/ping-networking-utility] *Pinging* involves sending an **ICMP echo request** to the target host and waiting for an **ICMP echo reply**.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/ping-networking-utility] The program reports errors, packet loss, and a statistical summary of the results, typically including the minimum, maximum, the mean round-trip times, and standard deviation of the mean.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/ping-networking-utility] Command-line options and terminal output vary by implementation.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/ping-networking-utility] Options may include the size of the payload, count of tests, limits for the number of network hops (TTL) that probes traverse, interval between the requests and time to wait for a response.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/ping-networking-utility] Many systems provide a companion utility ping6, for testing on Internet Protocol version 6 (IPv6) networks, which uses ICMPv6.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/ping-networking-utility] The ping utility was written by Mike Muuss in December 1983 during his employment at the Ballistic Research Laboratory, now the US Army Research Laboratory.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/ping-networking-utility] A remark by David Mills on using ICMP echo packets for IP network diagnosis and measurements prompted Muuss to create the utility to troubleshoot network problems.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/ping-networking-utility] The author named it after the sound that sonar makes since its methodology is analogous to sonar's echolocation.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/ping-networking-utility] The backronym *Packet Internet Groper* for ping has been used for over 30 years.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/ping-networking-utility] Muuss says that, from his point of view, *ping* was not intended as an acronym but he has acknowledged Mills's expansion of the name.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/ping-networking-utility] The first released version was public domain software; all subsequent versions have been licensed under the BSD license.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/ping-networking-utility] The FreeDOS version was developed by Erick Engelke and is licensed under the GPL.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/ping-networking-utility] Tim Crawford developed the ReactOS version.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/ping-networking-utility] Any host must process ICMP echo requests and issue echo replies in return.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/ping-networking-utility] The output lists each probe message and the results obtained.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/ping-networking-utility] Finally, it lists the statistics of the entire test.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/ping-networking-utility] In this example, the shortest round-trip time was 9.674 ms, the average was 10.968 ms, and the maximum value was 11.726 ms.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/ping-networking-utility] The measurement had a standard deviation of 0.748 ms.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/ping-networking-utility] In cases of no response from the target host, most implementations display either nothing or periodically print notifications about timing out.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/ping-networking-utility] In case of error, the target host or an intermediate router sends back an ICMP error message, for example *host unreachable* or *TTL exceeded in transit*.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/ping-networking-utility] In addition, these messages include the first eight bytes of the original message (in this case, the header of the ICMP echo request, including the quench value), so the ping utility can match responses to originating queries.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/ping-networking-utility] An ICMP packet transported with IPv4 looks like this.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/ping-networking-utility] Can be used by the client to match the reply with the request that caused the reply.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/ping-networking-utility] Payload for the different kind of answers; can be an arbitrary length, left to implementation detail.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/ping-networking-utility] Most Linux systems use a unique *Identifier* for every ping process, and *Sequence number* is an increasing number within that process.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/ping-networking-utility] Windows uses a fixed *Identifier*, which varies between Windows versions, and a *Sequence number* that is only reset at boot time.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/ping-networking-utility] An ICMP packet transported with IPv6 looks like this.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/ping-networking-utility] The payload may include a timestamp indicating the time of transmission and a sequence number, which are not found in this example.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/ping-networking-utility] This allows ping to compute the round-trip time in a stateless manner without needing to record the time of transmission of each packet.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/ping-networking-utility] The payload may also include a *magic packet* for the Wake-on-LAN protocol, but the minimum payload, in that case, is longer than shown.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/ping-networking-utility] The *Echo Request* typically does not receive any reply if the host was sleeping in hibernation state, but the host still wakes up from sleep state if its interface is configured to accept wakeup requests.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/ping-networking-utility] If the host is already active and configured to allow replies to incoming ICMP *Echo Request* packets, the returned reply should include the same payload.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/ping-networking-utility] This may be used to detect that the remote host was effectively woken up by repeating a new request after some delay to allow the host to resume its network services.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/ping-networking-utility] If the host was just sleeping in a low-power active state, a single request wakes up that host just enough to allow its *Echo Reply* service to reply instantly if that service was enabled.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/ping-networking-utility] The host does not need to wake up all devices completely and may return to low-power mode after a short delay.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/ping-networking-utility] Such a configuration may be used to avoid a host entering hibernation state, with much longer wake-up delay, after some time passed in low power active mode.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/ping-networking-utility] A packet including IP and ICMP headers must not be greater than the maximum transmission unit of the network, or risk being fragmented.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/ping-networking-utility] To conduct a denial-of-service attack, an attacker may send ping requests as fast as possible, possibly overwhelming the victim with ICMP echo requests.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/ping-networking-utility] Ping requests to multiple addresses, ping sweeps, may be used to obtain a list of all hosts on a network.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/synthetic-monitoring] In software design, web design, and electronic product design, **synthetic monitoring** (also known as ***active monitoring** or **proactive monitoring***) is a monitoring technique that is done by using a simulation or scripted recordings of transactions.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/synthetic-monitoring] Behavioral scripts (or paths) are created to simulate an action or path that a customer or end user would take on a site, application, or other software (or even hardware).
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/synthetic-monitoring] Those paths are then continuously monitored at specified intervals for performance, such as functionality, availability, and response time measures.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/synthetic-monitoring] Synthetic monitoring enables a webmaster or an IT/Operations professional to identify problems and determine if a website or application is slow or experiencing downtime before that problem affects actual end users or customers.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/synthetic-monitoring] This type of monitoring does not require actual traffic, thus the name synthetic, as it enables companies to test applications 24x7, or test new applications prior to a live customer-facing launch.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/synthetic-monitoring] Because synthetic monitoring is a simulation of typical user behavior or navigation through a website, it is often best used to monitor commonly trafficked paths and critical business processes.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/synthetic-monitoring] Synthetic tests must be scripted in advance, so it is not feasible to measure performance for every permutation of a navigational path an end user might take.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/synthetic-monitoring] These scripts are then injected into the code of the application or website, which is then tested under artificial loads.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/synthetic-monitoring] This, of course, can be a contrast to actual load/traffic when the design goes live.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/synthetic-monitoring] In this case, real user monitoring is performed, where the performance metrics are tested against real loads.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/synthetic-monitoring] This is more suited for passive monitoring.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/synthetic-monitoring] Synthetic testing is useful for measuring uptime, availability, and response time of critical pages and transactions (how a site performs from all geographies) but doesn't monitor or capture actual end user interactions, see Website monitoring.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/synthetic-monitoring] Synthetic monitoring will report myriad metrics, and it's up to the a webmaster or an IT/Operations professional to identify which ones are most important.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/synthetic-monitoring] Common metrics from synthetic website monitoring includes Time to First Byte, Speed Index, Time to Interactive, and Page Complete.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/synthetic-monitoring] Demand for synthetic monitoring has grown exponentially corresponding to the underlying growth in websites/applications.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/synthetic-monitoring] IT/Operations staff need mechanisms to identify health and performance issues in advance of their customers identifying and reporting them to avoid customer satisfaction issues.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/synthetic-monitoring] To accomplish this they can write custom simulation scripts, or leverage the growing number of commercial synthetic monitoring solutions.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/synthetic-monitoring] By implementing Synthetic Monitoring IT/Operations staffs are able to identify application issues in advance of them becoming critical, and take remedial action.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/uptime] It is often used as a measure of computer operating system reliability or stability, in that this time represents the time a computer can be left unattended without crashing or needing to be rebooted for administrative or maintenance purposes.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/uptime] Conversely, long uptime may indicate negligence, because some critical updates can require reboots on some platforms.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/uptime] In 2005, Novell reported a server with a 6-year uptime.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/uptime] This level of uptime is common when servers are maintained under an industrial context and host critical applications such as banking systems.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/uptime] Netcraft maintains the uptime records for many thousands of web hosting computers.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/uptime] A server running Novell NetWare has been reported to have been shut down after 16 years of uptime due to a failing hard disk.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/uptime] Most Unix-like systems including Linux, FreeBSD, Mac OS X, and SySVr4 have the *uptime* command.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/uptime] This command originated in 3.0BSD and has become ubiquitous among Unix systems ever since.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/uptime] Despite almost always providing the same collection of information and being so ubiquitous, it is not part of any Unix-related standard, neither SUS nor POSIX.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/uptime] On Linux, an *uptime* command is part of GNU coreutils, BusyBox and Toybox.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/uptime] On BSD, the *uptime* command is hard link to the *w* program.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/uptime] The *w* program is based on the RSTS/E, TOPS-10, and TOPS-20 SYSTAT program.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/uptime] Each Unix-like system also has its own private interfaces for obtaining the system uptime.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/uptime] On Linux, several procfs files provide information on the system uptime.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/uptime] The main file is `/proc/uptime`, but `/proc/stat` provides related information too.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/uptime] The first number is the total number of seconds the system has been up.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/uptime] The second number is how much of that time the machine has spent idle, in seconds.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/uptime] On multi-core systems (and some Linux versions) the second number is the sum of the idle time accumulated by each CPU.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/uptime] The C API for uptime information is `sysinfo()`.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/uptime] On BSD systems and macOS (a combination of BSD and XNU parts), the uptime information is available from the sysctl system, both in the form of the *sysctl* command and the `sysctl()` C function.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/uptime] macOS also provides the uptime as `clock_gettime(CLOCK_MONOTONIC_RAW)`, a POSIX interface with implementation-defined starting point; macOS sets the starting point at system boot.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/uptime] `mach_timebase_info()` and `CACurrentMediaTime()` are additional ways to access the same raw monotonic clock.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/uptime] On FreeBSD (but not macOS), the kernel exports three symbols that can be used as `extern` variables in C to obtain the boot time and uptime.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/uptime] They are called `boottime`, `time_second`, and `time_uptime`.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/uptime] These require no function call at all to use, unlike `sysctl()`.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/uptime] Higher-precision uptime is provided from functions such as `microuptime()`.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/uptime] Some versions of Microsoft Windows include an uptime field in Windows Task Manager, under the "Performance" tab.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/uptime] The format is D:HH:MM:SS (days, hours, minutes, seconds).
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/uptime] The output of the `systeminfo` command includes a "System Up Time" or "System Boot Time" field.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/uptime] The exact text and format are dependent on the language and locale.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/uptime] The time given by `systeminfo` is not reliable.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/uptime] It does not take into account time spent in sleep or hibernation.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/uptime] Thus, the boot time will drift forward every time the computer sleeps or hibernates.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/uptime] The `NET` command with its `STATISTICS` sub-command provides the date and time the computer started, for both the `NET STATISTICS WORKSTATION` and `NET STATISTICS SERVER` variants.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/uptime] The command `NET STATS SRV` is shorthand for `NET STATISTICS SERVER`.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/uptime] The exact text and date format is dependent on the configured language and locale.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/uptime] Uptime can be determined via Windows Management Instrumentation (WMI), by querying the `LastBootUpTime` property of the `Win32_OperatingSystem` class.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/uptime] The timestamp uses the format `yyyymmddhhmmss.nnn`, so in the above example, the computer last booted up on 8 May 2011 at 16:17:51.822.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/uptime] The text "LastBootUpTime" and the timestamp format do not vary with language or locale.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/uptime] WMI can also be queried using a variety of application programming interfaces, including VBScript or PowerShell.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/uptime] Microsoft formerly provided a downloadable utility called `Uptime.exe`, which reports elapsed time in days, hours, minutes, and seconds.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/uptime] The time given by `Uptime.exe` is not reliable.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/uptime] The `uptime` command is also available for FreeDOS.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/uptime] On OpenVMS systems, the `show system` command can be used at the DCL command prompt to obtain the system uptime.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/uptime] The first line of the resulting display includes the system's uptime, displayed as days followed by hours:minutes:seconds.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/uptime] In the following example, the command qualifier `/noprocess` suppresses the display of per-process detail lines of information.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/uptime] The command output above shows that node JACK on 29 January 2008 at 16:32:04.67 has an uptime of 894 days 22 hours 28 minutes and 52 seconds.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/web-performance] Faster website download speeds have been shown to increase visitor retention and loyalty and user satisfaction, especially for users with slow internet connections and those on mobile devices.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/web-performance] Web performance also leads to less data travelling across the web, which in turn lowers a website's power consumption and environmental impact.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/web-performance] Some aspects which can affect the speed of page load include browser/server cache, image optimization, and encryption (for example SSL), which can affect the time it takes for pages to render.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/web-performance] The performance of the web page can be improved through techniques such as multi-layered cache, light weight design of presentation layer components and asynchronous communication with server side components.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/web-performance] In the first decade or so of the web's existence, web performance improvement was focused mainly on optimizing website code and pushing hardware limitations.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/web-performance] According to the 2002 book *Web Performance Tuning* by Patrick Killelea, some of the early techniques used were to use simple servlets or CGI, increase server memory, and look for packet loss and retransmission.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/web-performance] Although these principles now comprise much of the optimized foundation of internet applications, they differ from current optimization theory in that there was much less of an attempt to improve the browser display speed.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/web-performance] Steve Souders coined the term "web performance optimization" in 2004.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/web-performance] At that time Souders made several predictions regarding the impact that WPO as an "emerging industry" would bring to the web, such as websites being fast by default, consolidation, web standards for performance, environmental impacts of optimization, and speed as a differentiator.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/web-performance] One major point that Souders made in 2007 is that at least 80% of the time that it takes to download and view a website is controlled by the front-end structure.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/web-performance] This lag time can be decreased through awareness of typical browser behavior, as well as of how HTTP works.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/web-performance] Web performance optimization improves user experience (UX) when visiting a website and therefore is highly desired by web designers and web developers.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/web-performance] They employ several techniques that streamline web optimization tasks to decrease web page load times.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/web-performance] This process is known as front end optimization (FEO) or content optimization.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/web-performance] In addition to the techniques listed below, the use of a content delivery network—a group of proxy servers spread across various locations around the globe—is an efficient delivery system that chooses a server for a specific user based on network proximity.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/web-performance] Typically the server with the quickest response time is selected.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/web-performance] Web browsers open separate Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) connections for each Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP) request submitted when downloading a web page.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/web-performance] These requests total the number of page elements required for download.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/web-performance] However, a browser is limited to opening only a certain number of simultaneous connections to a single host.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/web-performance] To prevent bottlenecks, the number of individual page elements are reduced using resource consolidation whereby smaller files (such as images) are bundled together into one file.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/web-performance] This reduces HTTP requests and the number of "round trips" required to load a web page.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/web-performance] Web pages are constructed from code files such JavaScript and Hypertext Markup Language (HTML).
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/web-performance] As web pages grow in complexity, so do their code files and subsequently their load times.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/web-performance] File compression can reduce code files by about 40 percent, thereby improving site responsiveness.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/web-performance] Web Caching Optimization reduces server load, bandwidth usage and latency.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/web-performance] CDNs use dedicated web caching software to store copies of documents passing through their system.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/web-performance] Many website platforms, such as SiteGround, IONOS, Wix, and Hostinger, rely on global CDNs and caching technologies to deliver faster page loads across different geographical regions.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/web-performance] Subsequent requests from the cache may be fulfilled should certain conditions apply.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/web-performance] Web caches are located on either the client side (forward position) or web-server side (reverse position) of a CDN.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/web-performance] Web browsers are also able to store content for re-use through the HTTP cache or web cache.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/web-performance] Requests web browsers make are typically routed to the HTTP cache to validate if a cached response may be used to fulfill a request.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/web-performance] If such a match is made, the response is fulfilled from the cache.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/web-performance] This can be helpful for reducing network latency and costs associated with data-transfer.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/web-performance] The HTTP cache is configured using request and response headers.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/web-performance] Code minification distinguishes discrepancies between codes written by web developers and how network elements interpret code.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/web-performance] Minification removes comments and extra spaces as well as crunch variable names in order to minimize code, decreasing files sizes by as much as 60%.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/web-performance] In addition to caching and compression, lossy compression techniques (similar to those used with audio files) remove non-essential header information and lower original image quality on many high resolution images.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/web-performance] These changes, such as pixel complexity or color gradations, are transparent to the end-user and do not noticeably affect perception of the image.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/web-performance] Another technique is the replacement of raster graphics with resolution-independent vector graphics.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/web-performance] Vector substitution is best suited for simple geometric images.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/web-performance] Lazy loading of images and video reduces initial page load time, initial page weight, and system resource usage, all of which have positive impacts on website performance.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/web-performance] It is used to defer initialization of an object right until the point at which it is needed.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/web-performance] The browser loads the images in a page or post when they are needed such as when the user scrolls down the page and not all images at once, which is the default behavior, and naturally, takes more time.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/web-performance] Since web browsers use multiple TCP connections for parallel user requests, congestion and browser monopolization of network resources may occur.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/web-performance] Because HTTP/1 requests come with associated overhead, web performance is impacted by limited bandwidth and increased usage.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/web-performance] Instead of a website's hosting server, CDNs are used in tandem with HTTP/2 in order to better serve the end-user with web resources such as images, JavaScript files and Cascading Style Sheet (CSS) files since a CDN's location is usually in closer proximity to the end-user.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/web-performance] In recent years, several metrics have been introduced that help developers measure various aspects of the performance of their websites.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/web-performance] Modules to measure metrics such as TTFB, FCP, LCP, FP etc are provided with major frontend JavaScript libraries such as React, NuxtJS and Vue.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/web-performance] Google publishes a library, the core-web-vitals library that allows for easy measurement of these metrics in frontend applications.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/web-performance] In addition to this, Google also provides the Lighthouse, a Chrome dev-tools component and PageSpeed Insight a site that allows developers to measure and compare the performance of their website with Google's recommended minimums and maximums.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/web-performance] In addition to this, tools such as the Network Monitor by Mozilla Firefox help provide insight into network-level slowdowns that might occur during transmission of data.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/website-monitoring] Website monitoring companies provide organizations the ability to consistently monitor a website or server function and observe how it responds.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/website-monitoring] The monitoring is often conducted from several locations around the world to a specific website, or server, to detect issues related to general Internet latency, and network hop issues, and to prevent false positives caused by local or inter-connect problems.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/website-monitoring] Monitoring companies generally report on these tests in a variety of reports, charts, and graphs.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/website-monitoring] When an error is detected monitoring services send out alerts via email, SMS, phone, SNMP trap, a pager that may include diagnostic information, such as a network traceroute, code capture of a web page's HTML file, a screenshot of a webpage, and even a video of a website failing.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/website-monitoring] These diagnostics allow network administrators and webmasters to correct issues faster.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/website-monitoring] Monitoring gathers extensive data on website performance, such as load times, server response times, and page element performance that is often analyzed and used to further optimize website performance.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/website-monitoring] Monitoring is essential to ensure that a website is available to users, downtime is minimized, and performance can be optimized.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/website-monitoring] Some platforms, like Webflow, Wix, and Duda, handle hosting and monitoring internally, providing visibility into uptime and performance without requiring third-party monitoring tools.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/website-monitoring] Users that rely on a website or an application for work or pleasure will get frustrated or even stop using the application if it is not reliably available.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/website-monitoring] Monitoring can cover many things that an application needs to function, like network connectivity, Domain Name System records, database connectivity, bandwidth, and computer resources like free RAM, CPU load, disk space, events, etc.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/website-monitoring] Commonly measured metrics are response time and availability (or uptime), but consistency and reliability metrics are gaining popularity.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/website-monitoring] Measuring a website's availability and reliability under various amounts of traffic is often referred to as load testing.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/website-monitoring] Website monitoring also helps benchmark the website against the performance of a competitor to help determine how well a site is performing.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/website-monitoring] Website speed is also used as a metric for search engine rankings.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/website-monitoring] Website monitoring can be used to hold web hosting providers accountable for their service-level agreements.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/website-monitoring] Most web hosts offer a 99.9% uptime guarantee and when uptime is less than that, individuals can be refunded for the excessive downtime.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/website-monitoring] Not all hosts will refund individuals for excessive downtime so one must become familiar with the terms of service of their host.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/website-monitoring] Most paid website monitoring services will also offer security features such as virus and malware scanning which is of growing importance as websites become more complicated and integral to the business.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/website-monitoring] Website monitoring can be done from both *inside* and *outside* of a corporate firewall.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/website-monitoring] Traditional network management solutions focus on *inside the firewall monitoring*, whereas *external performance monitoring* will test and monitor performance issues across the Internet backbone and in some cases all the way to the end-user.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/website-monitoring] Third-party website performance monitoring solutions can monitor internal (behind the firewall), external (customer-facing), or cloud-based Web applications.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/website-monitoring] Inside the firewall, monitoring is done by special hardware appliances which can help you determine if your internal applications’ sluggish performance is caused by: the design of applications, internal infrastructure, internal applications or connections to any public Internet.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/website-monitoring] External performance monitoring is also known as end-user monitoring or end-to-end performance monitoring.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/website-monitoring] Real user monitoring measures the performance and availability experienced by actual users, diagnoses individual incidents, and tracks the impact of a change.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/website-monitoring] A website monitoring service can check other internet protocols besides HTTP pages and HTTPS such as FTP, SMTP, POP3, ActiveSync, IMAP, DNS, SSH, Telnet, SSL, TCP, PING, UDP, SOAP, Domain Name Expiry, SSL Certificate Expiry and a range of ports.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/website-monitoring] Monitoring frequency occurs at intervals of once every 4-hours to every 15-seconds.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/website-monitoring] Typically, most website monitoring services test a server, or application, between a once-per-hour per once-per-minute.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/website-monitoring] Advanced monitoring services capture browser interactions with websites using macro recorders, or browser add-ons such as Selenium or iMacros.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/website-monitoring] These services test a website by running a web browser through a typical website transaction (such as a shopping cart) or a custom scenario, in order to check for user experience issues, performance problems, and availability errors.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/website-monitoring] Browser-driven monitoring services detect not only network and server issues, but also webpage object issues (such as slow loading JavaScript, or third-party hosted page elements).
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/website-monitoring] Implementation of time performance monitoring for the Apache HTTP Server is the mod_arm4 module.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/website-monitoring] Users of website monitoring (typically network administrators, webmasters, web operations personnel) may monitor a single page of a website, but can also monitor a complete business process (often referred to as multi-step transactions).
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/website-monitoring] Website monitoring services usually have a number of servers around the globe – South America, Africa, North America, Europe, Africa, Asia, Australia and other locations.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/website-monitoring] By having multiple servers in different geographic locations, a monitoring service can determine if a web server is available across continents over the Internet.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/website-monitoring] Some vendors claim that the more locations the better picture of your website availability while others say that three globally distributed stations are sufficient and more stations do not give more information.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/website-monitoring] Some monitoring services use multi-region consensus, where an alert is only triggered when a failure is confirmed from multiple independent probe locations simultaneously, rather than from a single location.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/website-monitoring] As the information brought by website monitoring services is in most cases urgent and may be of crucial importance, various notification methods, often known as "alerts" are used: e-mail, IM, regular and cell phones, SMS, fax, pagers, Skype, RSS Feed, SNMP trap, URL notifications, etc.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/website-monitoring] The Website monitoring market is very competitive.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/website-monitoring] There are 150+ active service providers and more than 100 are documented to have gone out of business.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/website-monitoring] Most of the providers offer a free plan with low-frequency monitoring.
[src:synthetic-monitoring-deep/website-monitoring] In recent years Synthetic Monitoring services have become widely available commercially, providing another vehicle to monitor the performance of specific web properties at a granular level.
